  <title>Algebraic Fractions</title>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Overview</title>
<p>In this lesson we reduce algebraic fractions and consider some simple examples using rational functions as models. We discuss the meaning of verical and horizontal asymptotes in aplications.</p></commentary>

<activity><title>Reducing Fractions</title>

<task><p>To reduce an algebraic fraction:</p>
<p><ol>
  <li><p><fillin/> the numerator and denominator.</p></li>
  <li><p>Divide the numerator and denominator by any <fillin/> .</p></li>
</ol></p></task>

<task><p>Reduce the fraction. Numerator and denominator are monomials, so no factoring needed.</p>
  <p><m>~~~~\dfrac{-12rs^2t}{-6rst^2}</m></p></task>

<task><p>Reduce. Factor numerator and denominator before canceling!</p>

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>You may be surprised at how feeble are your students' factoring skills. If it is important to you, you might need to provide additional factoring practice.</p></commentary>

  <p><ol>
  <li><p><m>\dfrac{5y^2-20}{2y-4} </m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\dfrac{6x^2-x-1}{2x^2+9x-5}</m></p></li>
  </ol></p></task> 
  
<task><p>Reduce. Use the formulas for factoring sums and differences of cubes.</p>
<p><m>~~~~\dfrac{8z^3-1}{4z^2-1}</m></p></task>

<task><p>Reduce. Look for negatives of binomials.</p>
  <p><ol>
  <li><p><m>\dfrac{2a^2-ab}{b^2-2ab}</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\dfrac{-4b^2-2b}{4b^3-b}</m></p></li>
</ol></p></task>
</activity>
  
<activity><title>Equivalent Fractions</title>

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>Even if you can get students to "factor before they cancel," they will probably still have great difficulty with this Activity. It is a good idea to go over all of these problems in class.</p></commentary>

<introduction><p>Which expressions are equivalent to the given fraction?</p></introduction>

<task><p><m>\dfrac{3}{5}</m></p>
  <p><ol cols="4">
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{3x}{5x}</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{3-x}{5-x}</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{30+x}{x+50}</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{30x}{50x}</m></p></li>   
  </ol></p></task>

  <task><p><m>\dfrac{v-1}{v+1}</m></p>
  <p><ol cols="4">
    <li><p><m>-1</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{1-v}{1+v}</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>-\dfrac{1-v}{v+1}</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{v+1}{v-1}</m></p></li>   
  </ol></p></task>

  <task><p><m>\dfrac{2w-6}{w}</m></p>
  <p><ol cols="4">
    <li><p><m>-4</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{6-2w}{-w}</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>2-\dfrac{6}{w}</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>-\dfrac{2w+6}{w}</m></p></li>   
  </ol></p></task>

 <task><p><m>\dfrac{3a+2}{3a-2}</m></p>
  <p><ol cols="4">
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{3a-2}{3a+2}</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{3a-2}{2-3a}</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>-1</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{2a+3}{2a-3}</m></p></li>   
  </ol></p></task> 
  </activity>

<activity><title>Horizontal Asymptote</title>

<introduction><p>Envirogreen Technology, Inc. decides to produce a new type of water filter for home use.They spend $5000 for startup costs, and each filter costs $50 to produce.</p></introduction>

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>Begin be reviewing the notions of revenue, profit, and cost. Make sure your students recognize the difference between price, variable cost, and average cost. Most students grasp the idea of spreading the start-up cost over the number of filters produced.</p></commentary>

<task><p>To help her decide on a selling price for the filters, the marketing manager would like to know the average cost per filter if they produce <m>x</m> filters.</p>  
<p>Compute the total cost of producing <m>x</m> filters:
  <md><mrow>\text{Total Cost} \amp = \text{Startup Cost} + \text{Cost of}~x~\text{Filters}</mrow>
      <mrow>  \amp = </mrow></md></p>
<p>Divide the total cost by the number of filters produced.
  <me>\text{Average Cost} = \dfrac{\text{Total Cost}}{\text{Number of Filters}} = </me></p></task>

<task><p>Sketch a graph of the average cost, <m>A</m>.</p>
